00032 /* MACROS that hide the C interface implementations from the
00033  * generated code, which makes it a little more understandable to the human eye.
00034  * I am very much against using C pre-processor macros for function calls and bits
00035  * of code as you cannot see what is happening when single stepping in debuggers
00036  * and so on. The exception (in my book at least) is for generated code, where you are
00037  * not maintaining it, but may wish to read and understand it. If you single step it, you know that input()
00038  * hides some indirect calls, but is always referring to the input stream. This is
00039  * probably more readable than ctx->input->istream->input(snarfle0->blarg) and allows me to rejig
00040  * the runtime interfaces without changing the generated code too often, without
00041  * confusing the reader of the generated output, who may not wish to know the gory
00042  * details of the interface inheritance.
00043  */
00044

00142 /* If we have been told we can rely on the standard 8 bit or 16 bit input
00143  * stream, then we can define our macros to use the direct pointers
00144  * in the input object, which is much faster than indirect calls. This
00145  * is really only significant to lexers with a lot of fragment rules (which
00146  * do not place LA(1) in a temporary at the moment) and even then
00147  * only if there is a lot of input (order of say 1M or so).
00148  */
00149 #if     defined(ANTLR3_INLINE_INPUT_ASCII) || defined(ANTLR3_INLINE_INPUT_UTF16)
00150 
00151 # ifdef ANTLR3_INLINE_INPUT_ASCII
00152 
00153 /* 8 bit "ASCII" (actually any 8 bit character set) */
00154 
00155 #  define           NEXTCHAR                    ((pANTLR3_UINT8)(INPUT->nextChar))
00156 #  define           DATAP                               ((pANTLR3_UINT8)(INPUT->data))
00157 
00158 # else
00159 
00160 #  define           NEXTCHAR                    ((pANTLR3_UINT16)(INPUT->nextChar)) 
00161 #  define           DATAP                               ((pANTLR3_UINT16)(INPUT->data))
00162 
00163 # endif
00164 
00165 # define            LA(n) ((NEXTCHAR + n) > (DATAP + INPUT->sizeBuf) ? ANTLR3_CHARSTREAM_EOF : (ANTLR3_UCHAR)(*(NEXTCHAR + n - 1)))
00166 # define            CONSUME()                                                                                   \
00167 {                                                                                                                                       \
00168     if  (NEXTCHAR < (DATAP + INPUT->sizeBuf))                                           \
00169     {                                                                                                                           \
00170                 INPUT->charPositionInLine++;                                                            \
00171                 if  ((ANTLR3_UCHAR)(*NEXTCHAR) == INPUT->newlineChar)           \
00172                 {                                                                                                                       \
00173                         INPUT->line++;                                                                                  \
00174                         INPUT->charPositionInLine       = 0;                                            \
00175                         INPUT->currentLine              = (void *)(NEXTCHAR + 1);               \
00176                 }                                                                                                                       \
00177                 INPUT->nextChar = (void *)(NEXTCHAR + 1);                                       \
00178     }                                                                                                                           \
00179 }
00180 
00181 #else
00182 
00183 // Pick up the input character by calling the input stream implementation.
00184 //
00185 #define     CONSUME()                           INPUT->istream->consume(INPUT->istream)
00186 #define     LA(n)                                       INPUT->istream->_LA(INPUT->istream, n)
00187 
00188 #endif
00189 #define         TOKTEXT(tok, txt)                               tok, (pANTLR3_UINT8)txt

00281 ANTLR3_API pwswdLexer wswdLexerNewSSD         
00282 (pANTLR3_INPUT_STREAM instream, pANTLR3_RECOGNIZER_SHARED_STATE state)
00283 {
00284     pwswdLexer ctx; // Context structure we will build and return
00285 
00286     ctx = (pwswdLexer) ANTLR3_CALLOC(1, sizeof(wswdLexer));
00287 
00288     if  (ctx == NULL)
00289     {
00290         // Failed to allocate memory for lexer context
00291         return  NULL;
00292     }
00293 
00294     /* -------------------------------------------------------------------
00295      * Memory for basic structure is allocated, now to fill in
00296      * in base ANTLR3 structures. We initialize the function pointers
00297      * for the standard ANTLR3 lexer function set, but upon return
00298      * from here, the programmer may set the pointers to provide custom
00299      * implementations of each function. 
00300      *
00301      * We don't use the macros defined in wswdLexer.h here so you can get a sense
00302      * of what goes where.
00303      */
00304     
00305     /* Create a base lexer, using the supplied input stream
00306      */
00307     ctx->pLexer = antlr3LexerNewStream(ANTLR3_SIZE_HINT, instream, state);
00308     
00309     /* Check that we allocated the memory correctly
00310      */
00311     if  (ctx->pLexer == NULL)
00312     {
00313                 ANTLR3_FREE(ctx);
00314                 return  NULL;
00315     }
00316     /* Install the implementation of our wswdLexer interface
00317      */
00318     ctx->mNL    = mNL;
00319     ctx->mOUTPUT_REDIR  = mOUTPUT_REDIR;
00320     ctx->mINPUT_REDIR   = mINPUT_REDIR;
00321     ctx->mEXIT  = mEXIT;
00322     ctx->mBACKGROUND    = mBACKGROUND;
00323     ctx->mCHANGEDIR     = mCHANGEDIR;
00324     ctx->mT__13 = mT__13;
00325     ctx->mCHAR  = mCHAR;
00326     ctx->mBLANK = mBLANK;
00327     ctx->mSTRING        = mSTRING;
00328     ctx->mTokens        = mTokens;
00329     
00334     ctx->pLexer->ctx        = ctx;
00335     
00338     ctx->pLexer->mTokens = (void (*) (void *))(mTokens);
00339     
00340     ctx->getGrammarFileName     = getGrammarFileName;
00341     ctx->free           = wswdLexerFree;
00342 
00343     
00344     
00345 
00346 
00347     /* Return the newly built lexer to the caller
00348      */
00349     return  ctx;
00350 }
